410","1365":"1365","1440":"1440","1393":"1393","1405":"1405","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Kirkleatham, Yorkshire, England":"Kirkleatham, Yorkshire, England","Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England","Saltash, Cornwall, England":"Saltash, Cornwall, England","Buckland St Mary, Somerset, England":"Buckland St Mary, Somerset, England"},"en":{"1393–1437":"1393–1437","1393–1455":"1393–1455","1410–1440":"1410–1440","1434–Female":"1434–Deceased","1365–1405":"1365–1405","1437":"1437","1434":"1434","1411":"1411","10 May 1434":"10 May 1434","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1365":"1365","1440":"1440","1393":"1393","1405":"1405","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Kirkleatham, Yorkshire, England":"Kirkleatham, Yorkshire, England","Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England","Saltash, Cornwall, England":"Saltash, Cornwall, England","Buckland St Mary, Somerset, England":"Buckland St Mary, Somerset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Maynard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and French: from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Mainard</i> (from ancient Germanic <i>Maganhard</i>, <i>Meginard</i>, from <i>magin-</i> ‘power, might’ + <i>hard-</i> ‘brave, hardy’). Compare   Mainard  .","Altered form of French <b>Ménard</b> (see   Menard  ), a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Minardi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Antonio, Carmine, Sal, Salvatore, Silvio, Corrado, Emanuele, Gino, Giorgio, Luciano, Natale.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of a personal name, <i>Minardo</i>, equivalent to   Maynard  ."]},{"name":"Minard","meanings":["English: variant of   Maynard  .","French: variant of <b>Ménard</b> (see   Menard  ), a cognate of   Maynard  ."]},{"name":"Minardo","meanings":["Italian: from the personal name <i>Minardo</i> of German origin, see   Maynard   1."]},{"name":"Mainord","meanings":["English: altered form of   Maynard  ."]},{"name":"Mainard","meanings":["English (Hampshire and Kent) and French: variant of   Maynard  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Maino","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Elida, Angelo, Mario, Rodolfo, Vito.","Italian (northern): from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Maino</i>, a short form of compound names beginning with the element <i>magin</i> ‘strength’, such as <i>Mainardo</i> (see   Maynard   1)."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Richard Maynard II was born in 1393, in Buckland St Mary, Somerset, England as the son of Richard Maynard. He married Lady Isabel Cotgreave in 1411, in Worcester, Worcestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1437, in Yorkshire, England, at the age of 44."},"et":{"1393–1437":"1393–1437","1393–1455":"1393–1455","1410–1440":"1410–1440","1434–Female":"1434–Surnud","1365–1405":"1365–1405","1437":"1437","1434":"1434","1411":"1411","10 May 1434":"10. mai 1434","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1365":"1365","1440":"1440","1393":"1393","1405":"1405","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Kirkleatham, Yorkshire, England":"Kirkleatham, Yorkshire, England","Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England","Saltash, Cornwall, England":"Saltash, Cornwall, England","Buckland St Mary, Somerset, England":"Buckland St Mary, Somerset, England"},"fi":{"1393–1437":"1393–1437","1393–1455":"1393–1455","1410–1440":"1410–1440","1434–Female":"1434–Kuollut","1365–1405":"1365–1405","1437":"1437","1434":"1434","1411":"1411","10 May 1434":"10. toukokuuta 1434","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1365":"1365","1440":"1440","1393":"1393","1405":"1405","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Kirkleatham, Yorkshire, England":"Kirkleatham, Yorkshire, England","Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England","Saltash, Cornwall, England":"Saltash, Cornwall, England","Buckland St Mary, Somerset, England":"Buckland St Mary, Somerset, England"},"fr":{"1393–1437":"1393–1437","1393–1455":"1393–1455","1410–1440":"1410–1440","1434–Female":"1434–Décédée","1365–1405":"1365–1405","1437":"1437","1434":"1434","1411":"1411","10 May 1434":"10 mai 1434","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1365":"1365","1440":"1440","1393":"1393","1405":"1405","Yorkshire, England":"Everwyck, Angleterre","Kirkleatham, Yorkshire, England":"Kirk